    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nIn Cython-generated FASTCALL function wrappers, the following pattern appears in the generated C code:\n\n```c\nconst Py_ssize_t __pyx_kwds_len = (__pyx_kwds) ? __Pyx_NumKwargs_FASTCALL(__pyx_kwds) : 0;\nif (unlikely(__pyx_kwds_len) < 0) __PYX_ERR(0, 1581, __pyx_L3_error)\n```\n\nDue to C operator precedence, this is parsed as:\n\n```c\nif ( (unlikely(__pyx_kwds_len)) < 0 )\n```\n\n`unlikely()` expands to an expression that returns `int` (0 or 1), which is **never `< 0`**.\nThe condition is always false — the negative-length error check is completely dead code and never triggers.\n\nCoverity static analysis reports this as `CONSTANT_EXPRESSION_RESULT`:\n> `!!__pyx_kwds_len < 0` is always false regardless of the values of its operands. This occurs as the logical operand of `if`.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```cython\n# Any Python function with keyword arguments compiled with FASTCALL support\n# triggers this pattern in the generated C wrapper.\n\ndef example(self, value):\n    pass\n```\nThe generated C code will contain:\n```c\nconst Py_ssize_t __pyx_kwds_len = (__pyx_kwds) ? __Pyx_NumKwargs_FASTCALL(__pyx_kwds) : 0;\nif (unlikely(__pyx_kwds_len) < 0) __PYX_ERR(...)   // <- bug here\n```\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nThe generated code should correctly guard against a negative keyword argument count:\n\n```c\nif (unlikely(__pyx_kwds_len < 0)) __PYX_ERR(0, 1581, __pyx_L3_error)\n```\n\nThis ensures the comparison happens *before* being passed to `unlikely()`, not after.\n\n### OS\n\nLinux\n\n### Python version\n\n3.11.10\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
